  "prompt": "Why did Ian Mckellen have emotional breakdowns when on set on the Hobbit?",
  "response": "Ian McKellen had emotional breakdowns during the filming of \"The Hobbit\" trilogy primarily due to the extensive use of green screen technology, which was very different from his experience filming \"The Lord of the Rings\" trilogy. He found the isolated and technical nature of acting against green screens extremely challenging and frustrating.\n\nIn \"The Lord of the Rings,\" many scenes were filmed on practical sets with real environments, whereas \"The Hobbit\" relied much more heavily on CGI and green screen technology. McKellen struggled with the lack of physical interaction and context, which made acting more difficult and less organic.\n\nDuring one particularly difficult moment, he was reportedly so overwhelmed that he broke down and cried, feeling isolated and disconnious from the filmmaking process. He later spoke publicly about how challenging and emotionally taxing the green screen experience was for him.\n\nThe drastic change in filmmaking techniques between the two trilogies, combined with the more technical and less immersive environment, contributed to his emotional struggles during the production of \"The Hobbit.\"",
